President Barack Obama will be awarding Corporal William "Kyle" Carpenter, U.S. Marine Corps (Ret.), the Medal of Honor for his courageous actions while serving in Afghanistan. Carpenter will be the eighth living recipient to receive the Medal of Honor for actions in Iraq or Afghanistan. He will be honored for his selfless service and bravery. Carpenter was born in Flowood, Mississippi and enlisted in the United States Marine Corps in 2009. He served as an Automatic Rifleman and was medically retired as a Corporal in 2013 due to his wounds. He is currently a full-time student at the University of South Carolina. Carpenter's personal awards include the Purple Heart Medal, Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal, and Combat Action Ribbon. The Medal of Honor is awarded to members of the Armed Forces who demonstrate gallantry and extraordinary merit in actions against an enemy of the United States or in military operations involving conflict with an opposing force.